[src:razor-pages/asp-net-core] Blazor is a recent (optional) component to support WebAssembly and since version 5.0, it has dropped support for some old web browsers.
[src:razor-pages/asp-net-core] While current Microsoft Edge works, the legacy version of it, i.e.
[src:razor-pages/asp-net-core] "Microsoft Edge Legacy" and Internet Explorer 11 was dropped when you use Blazor.
[src:razor-pages/asp-net-core] Originally deemed **ASP.NET vNext**, the framework was going to be called **ASP.NET 5** when ready.
[src:razor-pages/asp-net-core] However, in order to avoid implying it is an update to the existing ASP.NET framework, Microsoft later changed the name to ASP.NET Core at the 1.0 release.
[src:razor-pages/asp-net-razor] Razor became a component of AspNetWebStack and then became a part of ASP.NET Core.
[src:razor-pages/asp-net-razor] The Razor syntax is a template markup syntax, based on the C# programming language, that enables the programmer to use an HTML construction workflow.
[src:razor-pages/asp-net-razor] Instead of using the ASP.NET Web Forms (.aspx) markup syntax with `<%= %>` symbols to indicate code blocks, Razor syntax starts code blocks with an `@` character and does not require explicit closing of the code-block.
[src:razor-pages/asp-net-razor] The idea behind Razor is to provide an optimized syntax for HTML generation using a code-focused templating approach, with minimal transition between HTML and code.
[src:razor-pages/asp-net-razor] The design reduces the number of characters and keystrokes, and enables a more fluid coding workflow by not requiring explicitly denoted server blocks within the HTML code.
[src:razor-pages/model-view-controller] Traditionally used for desktop graphical user interfaces (GUIs), this pattern became popular for designing web applications.
[src:razor-pages/model-view-controller] Popular programming languages have MVC frameworks that facilitate the implementation of the pattern.
[src:razor-pages/model-view-controller] One of the seminal insights in the early development of graphical user interfaces, MVC became one of the first approaches to describe and implement software constructs in terms of their responsibilities.
[src:razor-pages/model-view-controller] Trygve Reenskaug created MVC while working on Smalltalk-79 as a visiting scientist at the Xerox Palo Alto Research Center (PARC) in the late 1970s.
[src:razor-pages/model-view-controller] He wanted a pattern that could be used to structure any program where users interact with a large, convoluted data set.
[src:razor-pages/model-view-controller] His design initially had four parts: Model, view, thing, and editor.
[src:razor-pages/model-view-controller] After discussing it with the other Smalltalk developers, he and the rest of the group settled on model, view, and controller instead.
[src:razor-pages/model-view-controller] In their final design, a model represents some part of the program purely and intuitively.
[src:razor-pages/model-view-controller] A view is a visual representation of a model, retrieving data from the model to display to the user and passing requests back and forth between the user and the model.
[src:razor-pages/model-view-controller] A controller is an organizational part of the user interface that lays out and coordinates multiple Views on the screen, and which receives user input and sends the appropriate messages to its underlying Views.
[src:razor-pages/model-view-controller] This design also includes an Editor as a specialized kind of controller used to modify a particular view, and which is created through that view.
[src:razor-pages/model-view-controller] Smalltalk-80 supports a version of MVC that evolved from this one.
[src:razor-pages/model-view-controller] It provides abstract `view` and `controller` classes as well as various concrete subclasses of each that represent different generic widgets.
[src:razor-pages/model-view-controller] In this scheme, a `View` represents some way of displaying information to the user, and a `controller` represents some way for the user to interact with a `view`.
[src:razor-pages/model-view-controller] A `view` is also coupled to a model object, but the structure of that object is left up to the application programmer.
[src:razor-pages/model-view-controller] The Smalltalk-80 environment also includes an "MVC Inspector", a development tool for viewing the structure of a given model, view, and controller side-by-side.
[src:razor-pages/model-view-controller] In 1988, an article in *The Journal of Object Technology* (JOT) by two ex-PARC employees presented MVC as a general "programming paradigm and methodology" for Smalltalk-80 developers.
[src:razor-pages/model-view-controller] However, their scheme differed from both Reenskaug et al.'s and that presented by the Smalltalk-80 reference books.
[src:razor-pages/model-view-controller] They defined a view as covering any graphical concern, with a controller being a more abstract, generally invisible object that receives user input and interacts with one or many views and only one model.
[src:razor-pages/model-view-controller] The MVC pattern subsequently evolved, giving rise to variants such as hierarchical model–view–controller (HMVC), model–view–adapter (MVA), model–view–presenter (MVP), model–view–viewmodel (MVVM), and others that adapted MVC to different contexts.
[src:razor-pages/model-view-controller] The use of the MVC pattern in web applications grew after the introduction of NeXT's WebObjects in 1996, which was originally written in Objective-C (that borrowed heavily from Smalltalk) and helped enforce MVC principles.
[src:razor-pages/model-view-controller] Later, the MVC pattern became popular with Java developers when WebObjects was ported to Java.
[src:razor-pages/model-view-controller] Later frameworks for Java, such as Spring (released in October 2002), continued the strong bond between Java and MVC.
[src:razor-pages/model-view-controller] This is close to the approach taken by the Ruby on Rails web application framework (August 2004), which has the client send requests to the server via an in-browser view, these requests are handled by a controller on the server, and the controller communicates with the appropriate model objects.
[src:razor-pages/model-view-controller] The Django framework (July 2005, for Python) put forward a similar "model-template-view" (MTV) take on the pattern, in which a view retrieves data from models and passes it to templates for display.
[src:razor-pages/model-view-controller] Both Rails and Django debuted with a strong emphasis on rapid deployment, which increased MVC's popularity outside the traditional enterprise environment in which it has long been popular.
[src:razor-pages/model-view-controller] It is the application's dynamic data structure, independent of the user interface.
[src:razor-pages/model-view-controller] It directly manages the data, logic and rules of the application.
[src:razor-pages/model-view-controller] In Smalltalk-80, the design of a model type is left entirely to the programmer.
[src:razor-pages/model-view-controller] With WebObjects, Rails, and Django, a model type typically represents a table in the application's database.
[src:razor-pages/model-view-controller] The model is essential for keeping the data organized and consistent.
[src:razor-pages/model-view-controller] It ensures that the application's data behaves according to the defined rules and logic.
[src:razor-pages/model-view-controller] Any representation of information such as a chart, diagram or table.
[src:razor-pages/model-view-controller] Multiple views of the same information are possible, such as a bar chart for management and a tabular view for accountants.
[src:razor-pages/model-view-controller] In Smalltalk-80, a view is just a visual representation of a model, and does not handle user input.
[src:razor-pages/model-view-controller] With WebObjects, a view represents a complete user interface element such as a menu or button, and does receive input from the user.
[src:razor-pages/model-view-controller] In both Smalltalk-80 and WebObjects, however, views are meant to be general-purpose and composable.
[src:razor-pages/model-view-controller] With Rails and Django, the role of the view is played by HTML templates, so in their scheme a view specifies an in-browser user interface rather than representing a user interface widget directly.
[src:razor-pages/model-view-controller] (Django opts to call this kind of object a "template" in light of this.) This approach puts relatively less emphasis on small, composable views; a typical Rails view has a one-to-one relationship with a controller action.
[src:razor-pages/model-view-controller] Smalltalk-80 views communicate with both a model and a controller, whereas with WebObjects, a view talks only to a controller, which then talks to a model.
[src:razor-pages/model-view-controller] With Rails and Django, a view/template is used by a controller/view when preparing a response to the client.
[src:razor-pages/model-view-controller] Accepts input and converts it to commands for the model or view.
[src:razor-pages/model-view-controller] A Smalltalk-80 controller handles user input events, such as button presses or mouse movement.
[src:razor-pages/model-view-controller] At any given time, each controller has one associated view and model, although one model object may hear from many different controllers.
[src:razor-pages/model-view-controller] Only one controller, the "active" controller, receives user input at any given time; a global window manager object is responsible for setting the current active controller.
[src:razor-pages/model-view-controller] If user input prompts a change in a model, the controller will signal the model to change, but the model is then responsible for telling its views to update.
[src:razor-pages/model-view-controller] In WebObjects, the views handle user input, and the controller mediates between the views and the models.
[src:razor-pages/model-view-controller] There may be only one controller per application, or one controller per window.
[src:razor-pages/model-view-controller] Much of the application-specific logic is found in the controller.
[src:razor-pages/model-view-controller] In Rails, requests arriving at the on-server application from the client are sent to a "router", which maps the request to a specific method of a specific controller.
[src:razor-pages/model-view-controller] Within that method, the controller interacts with the request data and any relevant model objects and prepares a response using a view.
[src:razor-pages/model-view-controller] Conventionally, each view has an associated controller; for example, if the application had a `client` view, it would typically have an associated `Clients` controller as well.
[src:razor-pages/model-view-controller] However, developers are free to make other kinds of controllers if they wish.
[src:razor-pages/model-view-controller] Django calls the object playing this role a "view" instead of a controller.
[src:razor-pages/model-view-controller] A Django view is a function that receives a web request and returns a web response.
[src:razor-pages/model-view-controller] It may use templates to create the response.
[src:razor-pages/model-view-controller] As with other software patterns, MVC expresses the "core of the solution" to a problem while allowing it to be adapted for each system.
[src:razor-pages/model-view-controller] Particular MVC designs can vary significantly from the traditional description here.
[src:razor-pages/model-view-controller] As Alan Kay wrote in 2003, the original motivation behind the MVC was to allow creation of a graphical interface for any object.
[src:razor-pages/model-view-controller] That was outlined in detail in Richard Pawson's book *Naked Objects*.
[src:razor-pages/model-view-controller] Although originally developed for desktop computing, MVC has been widely adopted as a design for World Wide Web applications in major programming languages.
[src:razor-pages/model-view-controller] Several web frameworks have been created that enforce the pattern.
[src:razor-pages/model-view-controller] These software frameworks vary in their interpretations, mainly in the way that the MVC responsibilities are divided between the client and server.
[src:razor-pages/model-view-controller] Early MVC frameworks took a thin client approach that placed almost the entire model, view and controller logic on the server.
[src:razor-pages/model-view-controller] In this approach, the client sends hyperlink requests or form submissions to the controller and then receives a complete and updated web page (or other document) from the view; the model exists entirely on the server.
[src:razor-pages/model-view-controller] Later frameworks have allowed the MVC components to execute partly on the client, using Ajax to synchronize data.
[src:razor-pages/template-processor] A **template processor** (also known as a **template engine** or **template parser**) is software designed to combine *template*s with data (defined by a data model) to produce resulting documents or programs.
[src:razor-pages/template-processor] The language that the templates are written in is known as a **template language** or **templating language**.
[src:razor-pages/template-processor] For purposes of this article, a result document is any kind of formatted output, including documents, web pages, or source code (in source code generation), either in whole or in fragments.
[src:razor-pages/template-processor] A template engine is ordinarily included as a part of a web template system or application framework, and may be used also as a preprocessor or filter.
[src:razor-pages/template-processor] Template engines typically include features common to most high-level programming languages, with an emphasis on features for processing plain text.
[src:razor-pages/template-processor] The templating languages are generally simple substitution-only languages, in contrast to the more sophisticated facilities in full-blown template processors, but may contain some logic.
[src:razor-pages/template-processor] Simple examples include ‘printf’ print format strings, found in many programming languages, and snippets, found in a number of text editors and source code editors.
[src:razor-pages/template-processor] In word processors, templates are a common feature, while automatic filling in of the templates is often referred to as mail merge.
[src:razor-pages/template-processor] An illustrative example of the complementary nature of parsing and templating is the `s` (substitute) command in the sed text processor, originating from search-and-replace in the ed text editor.
[src:razor-pages/template-processor] For example, `s/(cat|dog)s?/\1s/g` replaces all occurrences of "cat" or "dog" with "cats" or "dogs", without duplicating an existing "s": `(cat|dog)` is the 1st (and only) sub-expression in the regexp, and `\1` in the format string substitutes this into the output.
[src:razor-pages/template-processor] This may be a relational database, a source file such as XML, an alternate format of flat file database, a spreadsheet or any of other various sources of preformatted data.
[src:razor-pages/template-processor] Some template processing systems are limited in the types of data that can be used.
[src:razor-pages/template-processor] Others are designed for maximum flexibility and allow many different types of data.
[src:razor-pages/template-processor] Additionally some template engines allow additional configuration options.
[src:razor-pages/template-processor] These may consist of an entire document or a document fragment.
[src:razor-pages/template-processor] Template processing is used in various contexts for different purposes.
[src:razor-pages/template-processor] The specific purpose is ordinarily contingent upon the software application or template engine in use.
[src:razor-pages/template-processor] However, the flexibility of template processing systems often enables unconventional uses for purposes not originally intended by the original designers.
[src:razor-pages/template-processor] A **template engine** is a specific kind of template processing module that exhibits all of the major features of a modern programming language.
[src:razor-pages/template-processor] The term *template engine* evolved as a generalized description of programming languages whose primary or exclusive purpose was to process templates and data to output text.
[src:razor-pages/template-processor] The use of this term is most notably applied to web development using a web template system, and it is also applied to other contexts as well.
[src:razor-pages/template-processor] Document generation frameworks typically use template processing as the central model for generating documents.
[src:razor-pages/template-processor] A web template engine processes web templates and source data (typically from a relational database) to produce one or more output web pages or page fragments.
[src:razor-pages/template-processor] It is ordinarily included as a part of a web template system or application framework.
[src:razor-pages/template-processor] Currently, template processing software is most frequently used in the context of development for the web.
[src:razor-pages/template-processor] XSLT is a template processing model designed by W3C.
[src:razor-pages/template-processor] It is designed primarily for transformations on XML data (into web documents or other output).
[src:razor-pages/template-processor] Programming languages such as Perl, Python, PHP, Ruby, C#, Java, and Go support template processing either natively, or through add-on libraries and modules.
[src:razor-pages/template-processor] JavaServer Pages, Active Server Pages, Genshi (for Python), and eRuby are examples of template engines designed specifically for web application development.
[src:razor-pages/template-processor] Moreover, template processing is sometimes included as a sub-feature of software packages like text editors, IDEs and relational database management systems.
[src:razor-pages/web-template-system] A **web template system** in web publishing allows web designers and developers to work with *web templates* to automatically generate custom web pages, such as the results from a search.
[src:razor-pages/web-template-system] This reuses static web page elements while defining dynamic elements based on web request parameters.
[src:razor-pages/web-template-system] Web templates support static content, providing basic structure and appearance.
[src:razor-pages/web-template-system] Developers can implement templates from content management systems, web application frameworks, and HTML editors.
[src:razor-pages/web-template-system] The template and content resources are processed and combined by the template engine to mass-produce web documents, each with a similar visual format.
[src:razor-pages/web-template-system] For purposes of this article, web documents include any of various output formats for transmission over the web via HTTP, HTTPS, or another Internet protocol.
[src:razor-pages/web-template-system] A template processor (also known as a template engine or template parser) is software designed to combine *template*s with data (defined by a data model) to produce resulting documents or programs.
[src:razor-pages/web-template-system] The language that the templates are written in is known as a template language or templating language.
[src:razor-pages/web-template-system] With the model typically held in a relational database, the remaining components of the MVC architecture are the control and view.
[src:razor-pages/web-template-system] In the simplest of systems these two are not separated.
[src:razor-pages/web-template-system] However, adapting the separation of concerns principle one can completely decouple the relationships.
[src:razor-pages/web-template-system] A web browser and web server are a client–server architecture.
[src:razor-pages/web-template-system] Sites often also use a web cache to improve performance.
[src:razor-pages/web-template-system] In many implementations, template files contain variables or placeholders that are replaced with data supplied by an application when the page is generated.
[src:razor-pages/web-template-system] The source code of the template engine can be proprietary or open source.
[src:razor-pages/web-template-system] Many template systems are a component of a larger programming platform or framework.
[src:razor-pages/web-template-system] They are referred to as the "platform's template system".
[src:razor-pages/web-template-system] Some template systems have the option of substituting a different template language or engine.
[src:razor-pages/web-template-system] Programming languages such as Perl, Ruby, C, and Java support template processing either natively, or through add-on libraries and modules.
[src:razor-pages/web-template-system] JavaServer Pages (JSP), PHP, and Active Server Pages (ASP with VBScript, JScript or other languages) are examples, themselves, of web template engines.
[src:razor-pages/web-template-system] These technologies are typically used in server-side templating systems, but could be adapted for use on an "edge-side" proxy or for static page generation.
[src:razor-pages/web-template-system] Static site generators are engines that use flat text input files like markdown and asciidoc to generate a static web page.
[src:razor-pages/web-template-system] Examples of this include Jekyll (Liquid, Ruby), Hugo (Go templates), and Pelican (Jinja2, Python).
[src:razor-pages/web-template-system] Some hosted website builders, including Wix, Weebly, and Duda, provide template-based systems that allow users to create static and dynamic web pages through graphical user interfaces rather than traditional programming.
[src:razor-pages/web-template-system] HTML editors often use web template systems to produce only static web pages.
[src:razor-pages/web-template-system] These can be viewed as a ready-made web design, used to mass-produce "cookie-cutter" websites for rapid deployment.
[src:razor-pages/web-template-system] They also commonly include themes in place of CSS styles.
[src:razor-pages/web-template-system] In general, the template language is used only with the editor's software.
[src:razor-pages/web-template-system] FrontPage and Dreamweaver were once the most popular editors with template sub-systems.
[src:razor-pages/web-template-system] A Flash web template uses Macromedia Flash to create visually interactive sites.
[src:razor-pages/web-template-system] Many *server-side template systems* have an option to publish output pages on the server, where the published pages are static.
[src:razor-pages/web-template-system] This is common on content management systems, like Vignette, but is not considered out-server generation.
[src:razor-pages/web-template-system] In the majority of cases, this "publish option" doesn't interfere with the *template system*, and it can be made by external software, as Wget.
[src:razor-pages/web-template-system] People began to use server-side dynamic pages generated from templates with pre-existent software adapted for this task.
[src:razor-pages/web-template-system] This early software was the preprocessors and macro languages, adapted for the web use, running on CGI.
[src:razor-pages/web-template-system] Next, a simple but relevant technology was the direct execution made on extension modules, started with SSI.
[src:razor-pages/web-template-system] Technically, the methodology of embedding programming languages within HTML (or XML, etc.), used in many "server-side included script languages" are also templates.
[src:razor-pages/web-template-system] All of them are Embedded complex languages.
[src:razor-pages/web-template-system] There are also preprocessors used as server-side template engines.
[src:razor-pages/web-template-system] As for edge-side template and inclusion systems, "edge-side" refers to web servers that reside in the space between the client (browser) and the originating server.
[src:razor-pages/web-template-system] They are often referred to as "reverse-proxy" servers.
[src:razor-pages/web-template-system] These servers are generally tasked with reducing the load and traffic on originating servers by caching content such as images and page fragments, and delivering this to the browser in an efficient manner.
[src:razor-pages/web-template-system] Basic Edge Side Includes (ESI) is an SSI-like language.
[src:razor-pages/web-template-system] ESI has been implemented for content delivery networks.
[src:razor-pages/web-template-system] The ESI template language may also be implemented in web browsers using JavaScript and Ajax, or via a browser "plug-in".
[src:razor-pages/web-template-system] Many web browsers can apply an XSLT stylesheet to XML data that transforms the data into an XHTML document, thereby providing template functionality in the browser itself.
[src:razor-pages/web-template-system] The most simple form is transclusions (HTML frames).
[src:razor-pages/web-template-system] In other cases dynamic web pages are needed.
